bib.title: Polarization of protons inelastically scattered on24Mg, 52Cr and 58Ni.

free_txt: Two silicon surface-barrier detectors were fixed
each at an angle of 52 degr.
The relative non-statistical error induced by the
uncertainty in the determination of the peak content
was empirically found to be 2%. The fluctuations of the
beam intensity distribution on the first target cause
an error of 0.7% which was determined by a large number
of double scattering measurements on two gold targets.
The carbon polarimeter was used.
The carbon foils for the polarimeter were produced by
spraying a dispersion of colloidal graphite in alcohol
onto a rotating glass plate heated by infrared lamps.
To compensate for certain physical and apparatus
induced false asymmetries, for each polarization
measurement a control measurement was carried out, in
which the carbon target was replaced by a gold target.
Error in the absolute cross section definition
was approximately 10% which is mainly due to the
uncertainty in the target thickness. The error in the
shape of the excitation functions is smaller than 3%.

The gold layer on the targets was used to determine
the absolute value of the cross section.
Self-supporting magnesium targets were prepared by
evaporating natural magnesium with the aid of an
electron gun onto the polished face of an aluminium
cylinder and then peeling of the foil. For the
excitation function measurements the magnesium was
evaporated onto a 10mu-g/cm2 carbon backing.
